<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Nears OK of $1.83T Budget  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate is on the edge of blessing a $1.83
trillion budget for next year that will move lawmakers a step
closer to a campaign season full of battles with President Clinton
over spending and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was expected to approve the Republican-written
package today, after voting on perhaps dozens of amendments. Since
the House approved a similar plan two weeks ago, the GOP goal was
for Congress to pass a compromise measure by next Friday, in time
for lawmakers' spring recess.
</P>
<P>
   Even before senators completed the plan, the two sides were
attacking each others' fiscal visions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president has submitted a political budget,'' Senate
Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said Thursday of
Clinton's fiscal 2001 spending plan, which calls for more spending
and smaller tax cuts than Republicans want.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said Clinton's proposed increase in domestic spending
for 2001 was made ''either to embarrass us or make us spend
precisely what he wants, which is way too much.'' He wants about
$320 billion, or about 14 percent over this year's total and $30
billion more than Republicans say they prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the proposed GOP tax cut of at least $150 billion
over the next five years would consume virtually the entire budget
surplus, not counting Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats even introduced the $483 billion tax cut likely GOP
presidential standard-bearer George W. Bush has proposed for 2002
through 2006 and dared Republicans to vote for it. It was rejected
99-0, with Republicans wary that it could drain Social Security
surpluses both parties want to leave alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., who forced the voice on Bush's tax
plan, taunted Republicans, saying they should obey ''that noted
political philosopher, Tammy Wynette, who said, 'Stand by your
man.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton proposed, the GOP budget would trim the $3.6
trillion publicly held national debt by about $1 trillion over the
next five years, a reduction that most economists say should help
the economy by helping to keep interest rates low. Most of the debt
reduction would come from Social Security surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans would also boost spending for education, biomedical
research and other programs. But such details are really decided in
later bills. The budget, which does not require Clinton's
signature, only sets overall tax and spending targets for the year.
</P>
<P>
   By voice vote, senators agreed Thursday to add another $4
billion to next year's defense budget for a total of $311 billion,
or 7 percent above this year and $5 billion more than Clinton's
proposal. The added money would come from next year's projected
budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The provision, by Sens. John Warner, R-Va., and Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, would compensate for a $4 billion Pentagon boost the
House approved in a separate emergency spending bills that Senate
GOP leaders have decided to scuttle.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Durbin's vote on Bush, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
introduced language Thursday that was aimed at Vice President Al
Gore, the likely Democratic presidential candidate. It was approved
99-0.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's language stated opposition to a $3 per gallon gasoline
tax increase -- which Gramm said would be a way to eliminate
internal combustion engines. Gore proposed moving away from the
engines in his book, ''Earth in the Balance,'' but proposed no such
tax boost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
