<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 117.12; Dow Up 20.17  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today, led by another rally in
technology shares as investors snapped up stocks at bargain prices
after this week's sharp selloff.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index was
up 117.12 at 4,384.68. The Dow Jones industrial average was up
20.17 at 11,134.44.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 11.88 at 1,513.22.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks had another strong session today as investors
bought shares of companies whose prices were crushed in the steep
selloff Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm rose 7\ at 146] and JDS Uniphase gained 3 at 114{.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow joined the Nasdaq in benefiting from gains in the
technology sector. Leading the blue-chip index higher this morning
was Intel, up 4 15/16 to 134}, and Hewlett Packard, up 2\ at 150].
</P>
<P>
   ''This market continues to be driven by the continued enthusiasm
of technology investors,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief market
strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   That helped offset some weakness that came from a confusing
government jobs report, which investors struggled to digest.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the Labor Department reported the nation's
unemployment rate held steady at 4.1 percent in March, above the 4
percent that some economists had been expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures,
rose 0.4 percent to $13.60 in March, also in line with analyst
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But the government also reported that a surprisingly strong
416,000 jobs were added to business payrolls in March, the largest
gain since February 1996. Government analysts said a number of
special factors led to big gain in job growth, including the hiring
of census workers.
</P>
<P>
   Today's job report raised expectations that the Federal Reserve
would boost interest rates next month, the sixth time since last
June that the Fed will have moved to slow the economy and keep
inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan again cautioned
that the continuing tight labor market will force businesses to
offer higher and higher wages to woo workers, which could cause
inflation to accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I recognize that the unemployment rate did not drop, but the
job increase was a big number and I don't doubt at all that the Fed
will go ahead with another rate hike,'' Skrainka said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to next week, many investors were watching their
moves before the crush of the corporate earnings season.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 404.28 million
shares, down from 485.07 million shares on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.62 to 539.12.
</P>
