<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 121.96; Dow Up 12.41  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today, led by another rally in
technology shares as investors snapped up stocks at bargain prices
after this week's sharp selloff.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index
was up 121.96 at 4,389.52. The Dow Jones industrial average was up
12.41 at 11,126.68.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 11.70 at 1,513.04.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks had another strong session today as investors
bought shares of companies whose prices were crushed in the steep
selloff Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm rose 8} to 147~ and JDS Uniphase gained 5\ to 116}.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow joined the Nasdaq in benefiting from gains in the
technology sector. Leading the blue-chip index higher today were
Intel, up 5 11/16 to 135{, and Hewlett Packard, up 4~ at 153.
</P>
<P>
   ''This market continues to be driven by the continued enthusiasm
of technology investors,'' said Alan Skrainka, chief market
strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   That helped offset some weakness that came from a confusing
government jobs report, which investors struggled to digest.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the Labor Department reported the nation's
unemployment rate held steady at 4.1 percent in March, above the 4
percent that some economists had been expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures,
rose 0.4 percent to $13.60 in March, also in line with analysts'
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But the government also reported that a surprisingly strong
416,000 jobs were added to business payrolls in March, the largest
gain since February 1996. Government analysts said a number of
special factors led to big gain in job growth, including the hiring
of census workers.
</P>
<P>
   Today's job report confirmed expectations that the Federal
Reserve would boost interest rates next month in its ongoing effort
to slow the economy and keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   The market held its gains after Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan
defended the central bank's five interest rate increases over the
past 10 months in a speech in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to be careful to keep inflationary pressures
contained,'' Greenspan said in remarks to the National Technology
Forum. ''The evidence that inflation inhibits economic growth and
job creation is too credible to ignore.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to next week, many investors were watching their
moves before the crush of the corporate earnings season. Earnings
are generally expected to be quite strong, but in a nervous market,
investors are leery of even the slightest disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 589.96 million
shares, down from 691.48 million shares on Thursday. On the Nasdaq,
advancers were ahead by an 8-to-5 margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.65 to 539.15.
</P>
<P>
