<HEADLINE> Rail Board Sticks to Merger Freeze  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE MITTELSTADT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal rail regulators on Friday rejected
requests to lift their recent moratorium on new railroad mergers,
saying the freeze is necessary to give them time to craft new rules
to deal with a rapidly consolidating industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Surface Transportation Board rebuffed bids by Texas-based
Burlington Northern Santa Fe and Canadian National Railway to lift
the 15-month moratorium, which the regulators enacted just three
weeks ago. The two railroads argued that regulators lack authority
to refuse to accept new merger filings and should stay their
decision pending court review.
</P>
<P>
   BNSF and CN are seeking to merge in a $6 billion deal. The
transportation board's freeze was put in place just as the two
railroads were poised to file for merger approval.
</P>
<P>
   The board's refusal to stay its decision had been widely
anticipated, but the complaining parties were required to exhaust
their administrative options. Now, they will press their case in
federal court in the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not surprised but we're disappointed in today's decision
by the (transportation board),'' said BNSF spokesman Richard
Russack. ''We hope that the U.S. Court of Appeals will respond
positively and promptly to our recent filings.''
</P>
<P>
   BNSF last week filed a motion for a stay of the board's decision
and an expedited court review. CN will head to court early next
week with similar filings, said CN spokesman Jack Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will leave us no other option but to go to court,'' Burke
said of the board's latest action. ''And we'll do that
expeditiously.''
</P>
<P>
   The board, in its ruling Friday, defended its earlier decision
to impose a 15-month moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because our current regulations are inadequate to address what
will likely turn out to be the final round of North American rail
restructuring, we must adopt new rules before any major
transactions can be considered,'' the regulators said.
</P>
<P>
   Lifting the moratorium would ''force consideration'' of the
BNSF-CN merger before new merger rules can be developed, the board
said. ''We find that such a backwards process is not required by
law and would contravene the public interest,'' the board said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to freeze new mergers followed a four-day hearing
into the future of the railroad industry -- at a time when only six
major railroads are left in the United States and Canada. That
session was called after rail mergers in the 1990s, most notably
the 1996 marriage of Union Pacific and Southern Pacific, led to
widespread service disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   BNSF and CN contend they should not be penalized for previous
mergers' failings.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Surface Transportation Board: http://www.stb.dot.gov
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern: http://www.bnsf.com
</P>
<P>
   Canadian National: http://www.cn.ca
</P>
</TEXT>
