<HEADLINE> Harvard Names Jones Professorship  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Harvard University has named an
African-American music professorship after Quincy Jones, the
producer-arranger-composer who has a record 77 Grammy nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The Quincy Jones professorship of African-American music is
supported by a gift from Time Warner, Inc. Harvard spokeswoman
Rebecca Rollins did not disclose how much Time Warner donated, but
she said Friday that endowments of this type are ''usually $3
million and up.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the first endowed professorship in African-American
studies given to any American university by a corporation, Harvard
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The professor named to the post will hold a senior, tenured
position on the school's faculty with a joint appointment in the
music and Afro-American studies departments.
