<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of the Senate Budget Plan  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Highlights of the Republicans' fiscal 2001 budget
that passed
the Senate on Friday, and how it compares with the House-approved
plan and President Clinton's proposal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   --OVERALL: The Senate budget would spend $1.83 trillion next
year, raise $2 trillion in taxes and produce an overall surplus of
about $170 billion, which would be the largest ever. About $166
billion of the surplus would come from Social Security surpluses,
the rest from other programs. The House's and Clinton's budgets are
similar, though Clinton's would produce an estimated $190 billion
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   --DEBT REDUCTION: The Senate, House and Clinton would all assign
the nearly $1 trillion in expected Social Security surpluses over
the next five years to debt reduction. Each would also use part of
the non-Social Security surplus to reduce the debt, with Clinton's
$90 billion being the most.
</P>
<P>
   --TAX CUTS: The Senate would cut taxes by at least $147 billion
over the next five years, and perhaps $40 billion more if the
Congressional Budget Office boosts its surplus estimates this
summer. The House called for at least $150 billion in tax cuts but
left the door open for as much as $240 billion. Clinton proposed
$99 billion in cuts, plus $96 billion in tax increases on
cigarettes and some businesses.
</P>
<P>
   --MEDICARE AND SOCIAL SECURITY: Clinton has proposed creating
voluntary prescription drug benefits for all Medicare recipients,
with a net $31 billion cost over five years. GOP leaders say they
favor a plan that omits higher-income people, but have yet to
provide specifics. The House and Senate budgets would set aside up
to $40 billion for the costs, but do not require any action. And
none of the plans propose tax increases or benefit reductions that
many analysts say will be needed to prepare Medicare and Social
Security for the impending retirement of the baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   --OTHER SPENDING: The Senate would provide $311 billion for
defense next year, $4 billion more than the House and $5 billion
above Clinton. For domestic programs, the Senate and House would
provide about $290 billion, roughly $30 billion less than the
president wants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
