<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Painting Pulled From Capitol Exhibit  </HEADLINE>
By TIM TALLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A painting of a pope with an eye patch has
been replaced in a State Capitol exhibit after a conservative state
lawmaker called it anti-Christian.
</P>
<P>
   The oil painting by O. Gail Poole was scheduled to be part of an
exhibit of works by Oklahoma artists, said Betty Price, executive
director of the Oklahoma Arts Council, which sponsored the exhibit.
The exhibit opened Thursday night with another Poole work in place.
</P>
<P>
   Republican State Rep. Tim Pope complained about the painting
Tuesday as council workers were hanging it and dozens of other
works, Price said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stopped and looked at one that had the pope with the eye
patch. I stopped and asked what it meant,'' Pope said. ''Knowing
the arts council and their liberal agenda, it looks like the
blinded pope.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt that it was very anti-Christian,'' he said. ''Art is
what you see in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope said he questioned arts council workers about the meaning
of the painting but did not ask that it be pulled.
</P>
<P>
   The pope in the painting does not appear to resemble John Paul
II, the current Catholic leader, or any of his predecessors. It
depicts a man dressed in the ceremonial robes of the pope, with a
staff in one hand. The right side of the face is obscured in
darkness and the eye covered with a patch.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, one in a five-work series called ''Popepourri,''
was not intended to be a religious statement, the artist said.
</P>
<P>
   ''These people like that, they can find devils in anything,''
Poole said. ''It's just a shame that people can't just look at a
piece of art and enjoy it. It's kind of silly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
