<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-07 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Talks of Past Presidents  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton reflected on his
predecessors and their families Friday at a White House screening
of public television's ''The American President.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hopes the 10-part series that premieres Sunday
will ''give people a feel of the mixture of the personalities and
the character'' of the presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton frequently looked up from his prepared remarks to talk
about past presidents and their families and life in the White
House, from Franklin Pierce to Abigail Adams to Rutherford B.
Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I spend a lot of time reading the histories of previous
experiences in the White House and the biographies of some of my
lesser-known predecessors,'' he told an audience of about 150
people, most of them involved in putting together the series.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many great people have called this house home,'' he said.
''All of them so far have been white males of European decent. I'm
absolutely convinced that in the not so distant future, there will
be a woman president and a person of color who will occupy the
White House and the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   He made the same prediction Thursday in a speech to a group of
corporate executives.
</P>
<P>
   After viewing segments on Thomas Jefferson and John F. Kennedy,
Clinton thanked those involved with the series.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have reminded us that for all their achievements and all
their failures, they're also people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
